\begin_layout Standard
The copula generating method 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
eref{
\end_layout

\end_inset

chi1
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 generalizes the Gaussian copula 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{mcneil2005qrm}

\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}\sim N(0,1)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2t}$
\end_inset

 are jointly normal with correlation 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{1+(\ln\rho)^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus in this case the relationship between the percentiles is induced with
 a Gaussian copula.
 The Gaussian copula combined with Gaussian marginal distributions for the
 actual observed variables yields the usual factor model often employed
 in the study of correlated data 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{dnlawley1971fas}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The general form of the model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Setup 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
eref{
\end_layout

\end_inset

chi1
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can be written in the vector form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
s_{1t}\\
s_{2t}\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\end{array}\right)\alpha_{t}+\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
0 & \ln\rho\end{array}\right)\eps_{t}\ ,\label{mat2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 This suggests the generalization 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{c}
s_{1t}\\
s_{2t}\\
\vdots\\
s_{pt}\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
\vdots\\
1\end{array}\right)\alpha_{t}+\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
\ln\rho_{1} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & \ln\rho_{2} & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & \ln\rho_{p}\end{array}\right)\eps_{t}\ ,\qquad\eps_{t}\sim N(0,I)\ ,\label{mcop}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where the vector random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 has an appropriate long tail distribution, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general form of the proposed model is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y_{t}=F^{-}(\check{s}_{t})\ ,\qquad s_{t}=Z\alpha_{t}+\psi\cdot\eps_{t}\ ,\qquad\eps_{t}\sim N(0,I)\ .\label{gfac}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{s}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of percentiles of each component of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Further 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of independent random variables with a heavy tailed distribution.
 Further 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a vector with entries 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(\rho_{j})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}=1$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 notation indicates componentwise product, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is a matrix of factor loadings.
 The vector function 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the vector of marginal distributions determined the joint distribution
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular component 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G(s_{t})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}(s_{it})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the marginal distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{it}$
\end_inset

, component 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is similarly defined in terms of the marginal distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-}$
\end_inset

 denotes the vector of inverse mapping.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analogous to state space models in time series, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

state" vector, driving the tail dependence or tail correlation in the system.
 Thinking of a one--dimensional state, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 is large
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The marginal distributions in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are easy to describe and simulate from but functional forms for the specific
 cases of interest are usually not available.
 For example if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 contains chi--squared random variables and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eps_{t}$
\end_inset

 is normal then the marginal distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 correspond to that of linear combinations of chi--squareds and normals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When functional forms for the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are not available it is convenient to employ the nonparametric estimate
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\check{G}(s_{t})\equiv\check{s}_{t}\equiv\frac{1}{N}\ \ra(s_{t})\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{r}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

 are simulations from the second equation in 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
eref{
\end_layout

\end_inset

gfac
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ra(s_{t})$
\end_inset

 denotes the vector of ranks of each component of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector of marginal distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 may be functionally specified, up to unknown parameters, in which case
 the available data 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

 is used to estimate the unknown parameters leading to the estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\check{F}(y_{t})\equiv\check{y}_{t}\equiv\frac{1}{n}\ \ra(y_{t})\ .\]

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is small this estimate yields worthless tail probability estimates of either
 0 or 1 arguing for a functional estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Suggestions are in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Modeling the marginal distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section discusses the modeling of the marginals in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 It is possible to model each marginal by a different form.
 However in many applications differences will be confined to differences
 in the parameters, keeping the functional form fixed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Normal or log--normal marginals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi^{-}(\check{s}_{t})$
\end_inset

 is the standard inverse normal evaluated at each of the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{s}_{t}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 be vectors of means and standard deviations, respectively.
 Then the completed model is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{t}=\mu+\sigma\cdot\Phi^{-}(\check{s}_{t})\ ,\qquad s_{t}=Z\alpha_{t}+\psi\cdot\eps_{t}\ ,\qquad\eps_{t}\sim N(0,I)\ .\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 is normal then 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{s}_{t}=\Phi_{*}(s_{t})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 denotes a vector of marginal normals with means and variances as induced
 by the state equation.
 Hence the net effect of both measurement and state equation is to induce
 a jointly normal 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 with correlation matrix derived from the state equation.
 Hence this setup with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 normal, returns to the classical factor analysis setup 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{dnlawley1971fas}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the log--normal model 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 in the measurement equation is replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y_{t}$
\end_inset

 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 refer to the mean and variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
fref{
\end_layout

\end_inset

fig3
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 displays simulations from 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
eref{
\end_layout

\end_inset

chi1
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}\sim\chi_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 standard normal.
 Notice for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, there are many more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

+2" standard deviation events compared to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

-2" standard deviation events -- that is events that lie in the upper right
 hand square of each panel as opposed to the lower left panel.
 The bottom right panel shows moderate correlation for all occurrences below
 the means 0, with almost perfect correlation for above mean events.
\end_layout

