\begin_layout Standard

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}\sim\chi_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 normal\InsetSpace \space{}
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{fig3}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Pareto marginals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The the inverse of the Pareto distribution is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F^{-}(u)=b\left\{ (1-u)^{-1/a}-1\right\} \ ,\qquad0<u<1\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a>1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

 are the parameters of the Pareto.
 The mean of the distribution is 
\begin_inset Formula $a/(b-1)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus with Pareto marginals the model becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{t}=b\left\{ (1-\check{s}_{t})^{-1/a}-1\right\} \ ,\quad s_{t}=Z\alpha_{t}+\psi\cdot\eps_{t}\ ,\qquad\eps_{t}\sim N(0,I)\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are vectors of parameters and the first equation is interpreted in an obvious
 componentwise sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Other candidate marginal distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}^{-}$
\end_inset

 maps numbers between 0 and 1 to real numbers it is convenient to think
 of them as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
1'a+\sum_{i}b_{i}\ln\frac{u}{1-u}=1'a+\ln\prod_{i}\left(\frac{\check{s}_{it}}{1-\check{s}_{it}}\right)^{b_{i}}\]

\end_inset

 These have means 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 and variances 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}^{2}\pi^{2}/3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimating loss distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This leads to claim distribution.
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
c_{t}=\sum_{i=1}^{p}\frac{b_{i}}{(1-\check{s}_{it})^{1/a_{i}}}-1'b\ .\label{loss}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Simulating this loss is a three step process: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Simulating 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 realizations of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Computing the percentile ranks 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{s}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Combining the 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{s}_{t}$
\end_inset

 as in 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
eref{
\end_layout

\end_inset

loss
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formula is of independent interest.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{it}$
\end_inset

 is near 1, that is we are in the upper tail, then losses are likely to
 be huge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is uniform then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{b}{(1-u)^{1/a}}\]

\end_inset

 is Pareto In practice, for given parameter values, the losses 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{t}$
\end_inset

 and the loss distribution can be simulated.
 This yields relevant percentiles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Time series structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Up to now it is assumed the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 are independent random variables.
 An alternative is where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 has a time dependent structure.
 A simple example is a geometric random walk 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha_{t}=\e^{h_{t}/2}\ ,\qquad h_{t+1}=h_{t}+\eta_{t}\ .\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha_{t+1}=(\eta_{t+1})^{2}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Connection to previous literature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This setup 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
eref{
\end_layout

\end_inset

gfac
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is reminiscent of the usual factor model 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{dnlawley1971fas}

\end_inset

 often employed to study the joint behavior of variables.
 Similar to the ordinary factor analysis 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 spells out the way in which the heavy tailed factors manifest themselves
 into the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 and hence their percentiles 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{s}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formulation 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
eref{
\end_layout

\end_inset

