}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 displays the obvious connection to state--space models 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Harvey:89}

\end_inset

.
 In terms of this latter model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{t}$
\end_inset

 is called the state of the system which manifest in the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The signal serves to determine the percentiles 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{y}_{t}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The model is completed by specifying the marginal distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Goodness of fit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 observations on a vector random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2},\ldots,y_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The aim is to estimate the parameters in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose these two matrices depend on unknown parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step in the estimation is to convert the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 to percentiles.
 This is done either relative to a fitted marginal distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}$
\end_inset

 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}(y_{t})$
\end_inset

 is the vector of estimated percentiles, or by computing the percentile
 ranks 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{y}_{t}\equiv n^{-1}\ra(y_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 In the former case the estimated percentiles need not be exactly uniformly
 distributed although this does hold in the latter case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we use the 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{y}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Then according to the model 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{y}_{t}=G(s_{t})$
\end_inset

 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can plot the time series of percentile ranks.
 Actually what you do is simulate a large number of Given a vector of actual
 or estimated marginal distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 the percentile ranks are 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\check{y}_{t}=F(y_{t})\approx\frac{1}{n}\sum_{r=1}^{n}(y_{r}<y_{t})\ ,\qquad t=1,\ldots,n\ .\]

\end_inset

 The right hand side are the estimated percentile ranks in the situation
 if there is no estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{r}<y_{t})$
\end_inset

 is the vector of 1's and 0's indicating whether the corresponding component
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{r}$
\end_inset

 is than 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 or otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model states 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{y}_{t}$
\end_inset

 has the same distribution as 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{s}_{t}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 is generated as in 
