\end_inset

 it is easy to simulate the distribution of total loss given the parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 For each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 simulated values of the state vector 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}=Z\alpha_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t}$
\end_inset

 the corresponding estimated loss is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ell_{t}=1'(\hat{F}^{-}\circ\hat{G})(s_{t})=1'\hat{F}(\check{s}_{t})\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is a vector of ones and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}$
\end_inset

 are the vectors of estimated marginal distributions.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{G}(s_{t})=\check{s}_{t}$
\end_inset

 where the latter is determined with reference to the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 simulated 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ranking the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\ell}_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

 yields the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

 quantiles of the loss distribution.
 These quantiles are conditional on the estimated copula parameters in 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and the assumed or estimated marginals in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 However under a suitably large sampling effort 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, the quantiles will be independent of the approximation involved in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ell_{t}=1'F^{-}(\check{s}_{t})\ ,\qquad s_{t}=Z\alpha_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t}\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the vector of marginal distributions and 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-}$
\end_inset

 the vector of componentwise inverses.
 The marginal distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is either specified analytically, or determined empirically.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This case requires proper spanning of the actual losses.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 are the vectors of observed losses and 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{y}_{t}$
\end_inset

 the corresponding vector of percentile ranks.
 Then the total loss distribution is that of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{r}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ell_{r}=1'y_{r}\ ,\qquad y_{r}\check{=}s_{t}\ ,\qquad s_{t}=Z\alpha_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t}\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where the middle expression indicates the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{r}$
\end_inset

 are chosen from the components of the available 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{y}_{r}$
\end_inset

 is as close as possible to 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{s}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus in this case a large number of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 are simulated and converted to percentile ranks.
 Each observed 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{r}$
\end_inset

 is then associated with a simulated 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 with the same, or approximately the same, percentile rank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 is available (either the true marginal distribution or an estimate) then
 the distribution of losses is built up from 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ell_{t}=1'F_{*}^{-}(\check{s}_{t})\ ,\qquad s_{t}=Z\alpha_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t}\ ,\]

\end_inset

 Thus in this situation a large number of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 are simulated from the model from which the percentile ranks 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{s}_{t}$
\end_inset

 are computed.
 These 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{s}_{t}$
\end_inset

 are then used to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{t}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to each simulation 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 represents a vector of losses at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 on each of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 classes of business.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}\equiv1'y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the total loss and of interest is the quantile of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the percentile 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\pi<1$
\end_inset

.
 In applications typical values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 are 0.95 and 0.99.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate the quantile of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider first the two dimensional case.
 Percentile 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 in two dimensions is carved out of the unit cube as follows.
 Suppose firstly 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2t}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1t}$
\end_inset

 is the quantile corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\check{y}_{1t}=\pi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 is vector or marginal distribution functions and consider for vector 
\begin_inset Formula $0<u<1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x\equiv1'F_{*}^{-}(u)\ .\]

\end_inset

 This is the loss when each line of business is at the percentiles given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 Taking the total differential yields 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\de x=1'\de F_{*}^{-}(u)=\frac{-\de u_{1}}{f_{1}(y_{1})}+\cdots+\frac{-\de u_{p}}{f_{2}(y_{p})}\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $y=F_{*}^{-}(u)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\de x=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\de u_{1}}{f_{1}(y_{1})}=\frac{-\de u_{2}}{f_{2}(y_{2})}\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad-\frac{\de u_{2}}{\de u_{1}}=\frac{f_{2}(y_{2})}{f_{1}(y_{1})}\ .\]

\end_inset

 This is the slope of an iso--loss curve and is the rate at which the percentile
 rank 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 must be changed when the percentile ranks 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 is changed in order to maintain the same level of total loss.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the Pareto survival curve 
\begin_inset Formula \[
S(x)=\left(\frac{\theta}{x+\theta}\right)^{\alpha}\]

\end_inset

 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(x)=\frac{\alpha S(x)}{x+\theta}\ ,\qquad S^{-}(u)=\theta(u^{-1/\alpha}-1)\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad f\{ S^{-}(u)\}=\frac{\alpha u^{1+1/\alpha}}{\theta}\ .\]

\end_inset

 Hence in this case 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ln\left|\frac{\de u_{2}}{\de u_{1}}\right|=\ln\frac{\alpha_{2}\theta_{1}}{\alpha_{1}\theta_{2}}+\left(1+\frac{1}{\alpha_{2}}\right)\ln u_{2}-\left(1+\frac{1}{\alpha_{1}}\right)\ln u_{1}\ .\]

\end_inset

 Note if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}=\alpha_{2}=\alpha$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ln\left|\frac{\de u_{2}}{\de u_{1}}\right|=\ln\frac{\theta_{1}}{\theta_{2}}+\left(1+\frac{1}{\alpha}\right)\ln\frac{u_{2}}{u_{1}}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The negative of the slope, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\de u_{2}/\de u_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the (marginal) rate of quantile substitution (MRS).
 MRS depends only on the marginal distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}(u)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
newcommand{
\backslash
s}{
\backslash
sigma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The elasticity of substitution is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\s(u_{1},u_{2})\equiv\frac{\de\ln(u_{2}/u_{1})}{\de\ln(\mathrm{-\de u_{2}/\de u_{1}})}\]

\end_inset

 which is the percentage change in the relative size of the quantiles given
 a percentage change in the marginal rate of substitution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It would be nice to be able have a functional form for the components of
 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}(u)$
\end_inset

 so that RQS take a simple form.
 That is we estimate some nice functional form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
s(u)=\left(\sum_{i=1}^{p}a_{i}^{\frac{1}{\s}}u_{i}^{\frac{\s-1}{\s}}\right)^{\frac{\s}{\s-1}}\ .\label{ces}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Then the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 marginal distributions are parametrized by the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

 and the constant elasticity of substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $\s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see the meaning of the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 note 
\begin_inset Formula $s(0)=0$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $s(1)=\sum a_{i}^{1/(\s-1)}$
\end_inset

 which is the maximum loss.
 Further if 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is all zeros except in component 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 where it is 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 then (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{ces}

\end_inset

) reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{i}=F_{i}^{-}(u_{i})=a_{i}^{1/(\s-1)}u_{i}\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad u_{i}=F_{i}(y_{i})=a_{i}^{1/(1-\s)}y_{i}\]

\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}(y_{i})$
\end_inset

 is linear in the tail up to some maximum point 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=a_{i}^{1/(\s-1)}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the maximum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(\ln a_{i})/(\s-1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Iso--loss lines can be easily constructed from
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 we can easily determine the total loss to which this corresponds 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1'F^{-}(u)$
\end_inset

.
 By simulating from the copula of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 we can determine the frequency distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 In particular if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 is the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $G(s)=G\{1'F_{*}^{-}(u)\}$
\end_inset

 is uniform.
 In other words 
\begin_inset Formula $G\circ1'\circ F_{*}^{-}$
\end_inset

 is a mapping from copula distributed 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 to uniform random variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rate of quantile substitution depends only on the relative magnitudes
 of the densities.
 The rates are used to construct a iso--loss contours.
 Integrating the density of copula above the iso--loss curve corresponding
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 yields the probability of exceeding the loss 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sampling scheme is as follows.
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
s=1'\hat{F}_{*}^{-}(u)\ ,\qquad u\sim C\]

\end_inset

 Alternatively to find out what quantile a given 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 corresponds to, first construct the iso loss line corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Repeatedly draw 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and see the proportion of those 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $1'\hat{F}_{*}^{-}(u)$
\end_inset

