\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An improvement is where we first select 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 uniformly from 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\equiv F_{1}^{-}(u_{1})>s$
\end_inset

 then stop or alternatively if 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}(s)>u_{1}$
\end_inset

 then stop.
 If not compute draw 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\sim u_{2}|u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}(s-y_{1})>u_{2}$
\end_inset

 then stop.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the positive number 
\begin_inset Formula $s-F_{1}^{-}(u_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 This is the number 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}=F_{2}^{-}(u_{2})$
\end_inset

 has to exceed in order for the sum to exceed ...
 That is we want 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F_{2}\{ s-F_{1}^{-}(u_{1})\}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Accept--Reject sampling can also be used.
 We draw
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}u_{1}+p_{2}u_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 are prices.
 The prices may represent the cost of reducing each of the quantiles.
 To minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 subject to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the two dimensional case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aim is, to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 consistent with the observed percentile ranks 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}^{\#}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be done as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Junk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\lambda,\rho}$
\end_inset

 and our model is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y\sim C_{\lambda,\rho}\circ F_{*}\ ,\qquad y\sim F_{*}^{-}\circ C_{\lambda,\rho}\]

\end_inset

 Note the left hand side states how probabilities associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are calculated, namely 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P(y\le\tilde{y})=(C_{\lambda,\rho}\circ F_{*})(\tilde{y})\equiv C_{\lambda,\rho}\{ F_{*}(\tilde{y})\}\ ,\]

\end_inset

 while the right hand side indicates how one generates 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

: first you generate the uniforms according the copula, then you use these
 uniforms to interpolate out of the marginals: namely 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y=F_{*}^{-}(u)\qquad\mathrm{where}\qquad u\sim C_{\lambda,\rho}\ .\]

\end_inset

 Alternatively we can thus write the setup as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y=F_{*}^{-}(s^{\#})\ ,\qquad s=\Lambda f+D\eps\ .\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Connection to time series models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A time series version of this is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\check{y}_{t}=\check{s}_{t}\ ,\qquad s_{t}=Z\alpha_{t}+\Psi u_{t}\ ,\qquad u_{t}\sim N(0,I)\ ,\qquad\alpha_{t}\sim\chi_{1}^{2}\ .\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These generated 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 values are used to find synthesized 
\begin_inset Formula $s(y_{j})$
\end_inset

 values corresponding to the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{\#}(y_{j})=y_{j}^{\#}$
\end_inset

.
 We then measure 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\min_{\psi}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\| s_{j}-s(y_{j})\|^{2}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and construct the empirical distribution of the percentile ranks 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{j}^{\#}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

.
 Corresponding to each 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}^{\#}$
\end_inset

, pick out 
\begin_inset Formula $s(y_{j}^{\#})$
\end_inset

, which is the generated 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 with percentile ranks 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{\#}$
\end_inset

 closest to that of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}^{\#}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the log--likelihood of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,\rho)$
\end_inset

 based on 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}^{\#}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ell(\lambda,\rho)\approx\sum_{j=1}^{n}\ln f\{ s(y_{j}^{\#})|\lambda,\rho\}\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where here 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Copula properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a multivariate probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 as the vector of marginal distributions derived from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 In particular if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\equiv(y_{1},y_{2},\ldots,y_{p})$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F_{*}(y)\equiv\left(\begin{array}{c}
F(y_{1},\infty,\ldots,\infty)\\
F(\infty,y_{2},\ldots,\infty)\\
\vdots\\
F(\infty,\ldots,\infty,y_{p})\end{array}\right)\equiv\left(\begin{array}{c}
F_{1}(y_{1})\\
F_{2}(y_{2})\\
\vdots\\
F_{p}(y_{p})\end{array}\right)\ .\]

\end_inset

 In other circumstances the vector of marginals 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 is specified directly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A copula is a probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 on the unit hypercube with uniform marginals.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{*}(y)=y$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le y\le1$
\end_inset

 implying 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{*}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The usefulness of copulas, arises as follows.
 Consider a multivariate distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and define the distribution generated with copula 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and given marginals 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{C}\equiv C\circ F_{*}\ ,\label{Fx}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{C}$
\end_inset

 is a joint distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $(F_{C})_{*}=F_{*}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{C}$
\end_inset

 has marginals 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(C\circ F_{*})(\infty,\ldots,y_{i},\ldots,\infty)=C\{1,\ldots,F_{i}(y_{i}),\ldots,1\}=C_{i}\{ F_{i}(y_{i})\}=F_{i}(y_{i})\ .\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely given a joint distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with marginals 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}^{-}$
\end_inset

 as the componentwise inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 define the copula generated from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
C_{F}\equiv F\circ F_{*}^{-}\ .\label{Cu}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{F}$
\end_inset

 is a copula since it has uniform marginals: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(C_{F})_{i}(u_{i})=(F\circ F_{*}^{-})(1,\ldots,u_{i},\ldots,1)=F\{\infty,\ldots,F_{i}^{-}(u_{i}),\ldots,\infty\}=u_{i}\ .\]

\end_inset

 Every 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has a copula representation which is clear from 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F_{C_{F}}=C_{F}\circ F_{*}=F\circ F_{*}^{-}\circ F_{*}=F\ .\]

\end_inset

 Finally note 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C_{C}=C\ ,\qquad C_{F_{C}}=F_{C}\circ(F_{C})_{*}^{-}=C\circ F_{*}\circ F_{*}^{-}=C\ .\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Copula properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $C_{*}(y)=y$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim F_{C}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}(y)\sim C$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $u\sim C_{F}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}^{-}(u)\sim F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the componentwise vector of univariate monotonic functions then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C_{F\circ H_{*}^{-}}\equiv F\circ H_{*}^{-}\circ(F\circ H_{*}^{-})_{*}^{-}=F\circ F_{*}^{-}\equiv C_{F}\ .\]

\end_inset

 Hence copulas are invariant to monotonic transformations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The density associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{F}=F\circ F_{*}^{-}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{f\circ F_{*}^{-}}{\Pi(f_{*}\circ F_{*}^{-})}\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the density associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of marginal densitities.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\Pi f_{*}$
\end_inset

 (ie independence) then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ F_{*}^{-}=\Pi(f_{*}\circ F_{*}^{-})$
\end_inset

 and the density is identically 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Gaussian copula with correlation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the copula 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\Phi^{R}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi^{R}$
\end_inset

 is the Gaussian distribution with mean 0 and covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a correlation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Phi^{R})_{*}=\Phi_{*}$
\end_inset

, a vector of standard normal distributions, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\Phi^{R}}=\Phi^{R}\circ\Phi_{*}^{-}$
\end_inset

.
 The meta--Gaussian model is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
F_{*}(y)\sim C_{\Phi^{R}}\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad F_{*}(y)=\Phi_{*}(\eps)\ ,\qquad\eps\sim N(0,R)\ .\label{metaG}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is estimated using the average cross product matrix of the normits 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Phi_{*}^{-}\circ F_{*})(y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The meta--gamma model is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F_{*}(y)=\Gamma_{\psi}(1\eta+\Psi\eps)\ ,\qquad(\eta,\eps')'\sim\Gamma(\mu,\nu)\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a vector of parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi=\diag(\psi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\psi}$
\end_inset

 the vector of marginal distributions associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $1\eta+\Psi\eps$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Levy copula is 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{*}(u)=u$
\end_inset

.
 Thus it is a copula on the unit hypercube suitable extended to 
\begin_inset Formula $u>1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The independence and perfectly dependent copulas is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi\equiv\Pi\ 1_{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vee\equiv\min$
\end_inset

 respectively, where 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{*}$
\end_inset

 indicates the vector of identity functions.
 These arise as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C_{\Pi F_{*}}\equiv(\Pi F_{*})\circ F_{*}^{-}=\Pi\ 1_{*}\ ,\qquad C_{\vee}=\ .\]

\end_inset

 The perfectly dependent copula implies a single source of noise: 
\begin_inset Formula $y=F_{*}^{-}1u$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u\sim U$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is a vector of identity functions of one variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Any copula is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

symmetric" in the sense that if 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is the copula of 2D vector 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 then it is also the copula of the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 with the components interchanged.
 This follows since suppose the density associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $c(u_{1})\equiv1\equiv c(u_{2})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
c(u_{1}|u_{2})=\frac{c(u_{1},u_{2})}{c(u_{2})}=c(u_{1},u_{2})=\frac{c(u_{1},u_{2})}{c(u_{2})}=c(u_{2}|u_{1})\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a copula then 
\begin_inset Formula $C\circ(1-)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

survival" copula.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-)$
\end_inset

 is defined such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-)u=1-u$
\end_inset

.
 To prove this result note that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Factor copula models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest factor copula model is as follows.
 Given a vector of nonnegative weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\ge0$
\end_inset

, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula \[
1\eta+\Psi\eps\qquad\mathrm{where}\qquad\eta\sim\chi_{1}^{2}\ ,\qquad\eps\sim N(0,I)\]

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eps$
\end_inset

 independent and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi=\diag(\psi)$
\end_inset

.
 Further suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of marginal distributions associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $u\equiv G_{*}(1\eta+\Psi\eps)$
\end_inset

 is a vector of uniform, albeit dependent, random variables.
 Hence the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a copula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of this development we suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is generated by the marginals 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 and copula derived from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F_{*}(y)=G(\Lambda f+\Psi\eps)\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad y\sim F_{*}^{-}\circ C_{G}\ .\]

\end_inset

 These steps make it clear how things are structured.
 First, the factor scores are generated.
 Then transformed to uniforms and finally transformed from the uniforms
 to the things in the tails.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Generated practical copula structures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simulate the model for given 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 and given 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, we first generate the many values of the scores 
\begin_inset Formula $1f+\Psi\eps$
\end_inset

.
 These scores are then transformed to percentile ranks and these percentile
 ranks are used to pull out the corresponding values from the marginal distribut
ion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Initially suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\chi_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $G_{*}(1f+\Psi\eps)$
\end_inset

 one first simulates 
\begin_inset Formula $1\eta+\Psi\eps$
\end_inset

 and then applies the 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{*}^{\psi}$
\end_inset

.
 However a simpler, more practical procedure is simply to simulate a large
 number of 
\begin_inset Formula $1\eta+\Psi\eps$
\end_inset

 and then compute empirical quantiles corresponding to each component.
 Figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{uv}

\end_inset

 displays realizations in the bivariate case for four different values of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 In each case the first component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is zero while the second component is the given positive value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each of these figures was generated as follows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,\ldots,n=10000$
\end_inset

 generate 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}\sim\chi_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eps_{t}\sim N(0,I)$
\end_inset

 of order 2 and construct 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{t}\equiv1\eta_{t}+\diag(\psi)\eps_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute the quantiles associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{it}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Wang article
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a vector of losses (random).
 Assume from 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 you derive (componentwise) a vector of risk capitals 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 works componentwise.
 There are two rules for calculating capital: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Basel Accords: 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota'r(x)=\sum_{i}r_{i}(x)=\sum_{i}r_{i}(x_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
US Insurance NAIC RBC: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\sum_{i}r_{i}^{2}(x_{i})}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Company models: Individual probability distributions for a company's risks
 are quantified.
 Then assuming a correlation matrix the aggregate loss distribution is calculate
d yielding percentiles etc.
 The total economic capital is then distributed back to the business units
 according to 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\pi_{i}=\frac{\iota'Ru_{i}}{\iota'R\iota}\ ,\qquad\iota=\sum_{i}u_{i}\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of zeros except in position 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 where it is 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next states that yield spreads exaggerate default rates.
 Goes on to posit the model for the price of risk 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{t}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \[
h_{t}=\hat{\mu}_{t}+\lambda_{t}\sigma_{t}\ ,\qquad\hat{\mu}_{t}=\mu_{t}+\eps_{t}\ ,\qquad\cov(\eps_{t})=(\partial\sigma_{t})C(\partial\sigma_{t})\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a scalar stochastic process, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a correlation matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\sigma_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the diagonal matrix formed from the standard deviation vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the true mean value of the loss: ie 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t}=\E(x_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\cov(\eps_{t},\lambda_{t})=0$
\end_inset

 implying 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\cov(h_{t})=(\partial\sigma_{t})C(\partial\sigma_{t})+\cov(\lambda_{t})\sigma_{t}\sigma_{t}'\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Corner tail correlations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed measure of tail correlation proceeds as follows.
 take the percentile ranks and map to the z--scores ie 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{j}=(\Phi^{-1}\circ F_{*})(x_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 is bivariate, write 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 as the proportion of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 falling in the lower corner.
 The lower tail correlation is the solution for the off diagonal entry in
 the correlation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(\Phi^{R}\circ\Phi^{-1})(1\alpha)=\E[\Pi\{\hat{F}_{*}(x_{j})<1\alpha\}]\ .\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\E$
\end_inset

 denotes the empirical expectation (ie fraction).
 Why not try and find the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Copula factor model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\p$
\end_inset

 computes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

uniforms" of a random variable.
 Then for any monotonic transform 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\p\circ f=\p$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\p\circ\p=\p$
\end_inset

.
 Further for a monotonic decreasing function 
\begin_inset Formula $\p\circ f=1-\p$
\end_inset

 implying 
\begin_inset Formula $\p\circ(1-\p)=1-\p$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\p\circ-=1-\p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 a vector of weights.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is said to be generated by the copula factor model if 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\p(y_{t})=\p(\Lambda f_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t})\ ,\qquad f_{t}\sim\chi_{\nu}^{2}\ \mathrm{or}\ t_{\nu}\ ,\qquad\eps_{t}\sim N(0,\sigma^{2}I)\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix with diagonal 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality assume the first component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Different specifications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here show the effect of different 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 and perhaps replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda f_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t}$
\end_inset

 by eg 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda(f_{t})+\Psi\eps_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rank correlation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\R(y_{t})$
\end_inset

 is the rank correlation matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

: that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\R(y_{t})\equiv\cor\{\p(y_{t})\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimating the copula factor model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\p}(y_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 If we know the cdf 
\begin_inset Formula $\p_{x}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}\equiv\Lambda f_{t}+\psi\eps_{t}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}_{t}=(P_{x}^{-}\circ\hat{P})(y_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 However we don't know 
\begin_inset Formula $\p_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 However simulate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

 and reorder the simulated components of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1,\ldots n$
\end_inset

 to yield 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\p}(\tilde{x}_{t})=\hat{\p}(y_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 In other words we order the simulated components of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{s}$
\end_inset

 according to the order specified in 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the relationship of this to finding 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 such that the rank correlation is preserved.
 In this we simulate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 from the model and adjust 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 till we get a rank correlation for the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 equal to the observed rank correlation.
 Obviously this procedure cannot tell us anything about order of things.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we use the procedure of the last paragraph to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Then for the given 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 we simulate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{s}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

 and in turn 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 We use the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{s}$
\end_inset

 to infer about the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}=\Lambda f_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t}$
\end_inset

 we can do a PC analysis on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\p}(\tilde{x}_{t})=\hat{\p}(y_{t})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is our estimate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $+/\hat{\p}(y_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 If we know 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda f_{t}$
\end_inset

 then take
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the the principal components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\p}(y_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 These pick up the major directions of variation.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is estimated by the following steps: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the principal components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\p}(y_{t})$
\end_inset

 to yield say 
\begin_inset Formula $UDU'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is the first column of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 compute 
\begin_inset Formula $u'\hat{\p}(y_{t})\}\approx\p(f_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 This the vector of weights.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Minimize 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 we simulate 
\begin_inset Formula $1f_{t}^{s}+\Psi\eps_{t}^{s}$
\end_inset

 and reorder each scalar series in each simulation to yield 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}^{s}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\p}(x_{t}^{s})=\hat{\p}(y_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 interpolated back into the EDF of 
\begin_inset Formula $1f_{t}^{s}+\Psi\eps_{t}^{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The two variable case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate estimation consider first the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is two dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=1$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the correlation between the ranks the two components in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\p}(y_{t})$
\end_inset

 -- that is the rank correlation between the components in 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we want to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\cor\{\hat{\p}(1f_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t})\}=\cor\{\hat{\p}(y_{t})\}\ .\]

\end_inset

 Notice the correlation decreases with 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 So we simulate 
\begin_inset Formula $1f_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t}$
\end_inset

 and compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\cor\{\p(1f_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t})\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Put 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times n$
\end_inset

 vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}=\Lambda f_{t}+\Psi\eps_{t}$
\end_inset

 and without loss of generality 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi=\diag(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 For given 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\sigma$
\end_inset

 generate a simulated path of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 denote 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Note 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{s}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times n$
\end_inset

.
 Rank each row of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{s}$
\end_inset

 according to the ranks of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}^{s}$
\end_inset

 and redefine 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 as the standard deviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tilde{x}^{s}$
\end_inset

 where the latter subtracts the first row from the second.
 Cycle through this procedure as in Gibbs sampling to get a distribution
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 This is the posterior distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then calculate the units of each component in 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 and calculate its value in the empirical cdf of the corresponding component
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 To achieve this rank, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{it}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

 according to the ranks of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{it}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose this yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 This is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\eps_{2t}$
\end_inset

.
 So take the standard deviation of so as to get an estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the joint distribution is generated with the meta--gamma copula 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\psi}\equiv G^{\psi}\circ(G_{*}^{\psi})^{-}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maybe the model should be changed to something like this 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F_{*}(y)=H_{*}[1\Phi^{-}\{ G(\eta)\}+(\partial\psi)\eps]\ ,\qquad\eta\sim\chi_{1}^{2}\ ,\qquad\eps\sim N(0,I)\ .\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimation of copula parameters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Estimation and testing consists of the following steps: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute the empirical cdfs 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}_{*}(y)$
\end_inset

 and the percentile ranks 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}=\hat{F}_{*}(y_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}\sim\chi_{\nu}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}\sim N(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and form 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=1\eta_{i}+(\partial\theta)z_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

.
 Use the results to form an empirical estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{*}^{\theta}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use these to form an empirical estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}(\theta)=G_{*}^{\theta-}(u_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\eps_{t}(\theta)\equiv\frac{v_{2t}(\theta)-v_{1t}(\theta)}{\theta}\ ,\qquad t=1,\ldots,n\ .\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute the log--likelihood 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ell(\theta)=\sum_{t=1}^{n}\eps_{t}^{2}(\theta)\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(\theta)$
\end_inset

 is minimum 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are some assertions I think are true about the meta--gamma.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The means on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\eps_{i}$
\end_inset

 should not make a difference since we are transforming to percentiles.
 Or maybe it is just the relative means or something.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
By tuning the gamma's we can pretty much describe any chi-squared/normal
 behaviour 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The sum of independent gamma's is gamma so we can easily figure out 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\psi}$
\end_inset

 etc.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 then the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 approach perfect dependence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\rightarrow\pm\infty$
\end_inset

 then the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 approach independence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Weibull losses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the Weibull distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
u=F(y)=1-\exp\left\{ -\left(\frac{y}{\alpha}\right)^{\beta}\right\} \qquad\Rightarrow\qquad F^{-}(u)=\alpha\left\{ -\ln(1-u)\right\} ^{1/\beta}\ .\]

\end_inset

 indicating that if 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is uniform then the right hand transformation is Weibull.
 With this specification 
\begin_inset Formula \[
s(u)=\sum\alpha\left\{ -\ln(1-u)\right\} ^{\frac{1}{\beta}}\ ,\]

\end_inset

 Further note the density of corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $F(y)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(y)=\frac{\beta}{\alpha}\exp\left\{ -\left(\frac{y}{\alpha}\right)^{\beta}\right\} \left(\frac{y}{\alpha}\right)^{\beta-1}\ =\frac{\beta}{\alpha}\left(\frac{y}{\alpha}\right)^{\beta-1}\{1-F(y)\}.\]

\end_inset

 implying the product out the front is the hazard.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further.
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\de s=\sum\frac{\de u}{f\{ F^{-}(u)\}}=\sum\frac{\alpha\left\{ -\ln(1-u)\right\} ^{\frac{1}{\beta}-1}}{\beta(1-u)}\ \de u\ .\]

\end_inset

 which defines the iso--loss curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 are estimated for each marginal distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}(y_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 The mean and variance associated with the marginal distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 are then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\alpha\Gamma\left(1+\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\ ,\\qquad\alpha^{2}\left\{ \Gamma\left(1+\frac{2}{\beta}\right)-\Gamma^{2}\left(1+\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\right\} \]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Open question
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that 
\begin_inset Formula $s(u)=\sum F_{i}^{-}(u_{i})$
\end_inset

 for some appropriate functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The question is whether we can structure things such that this sum is nice.
 One procedure is where we first choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 uniformly and compute 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}^{-}(u_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 Next choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\sim u_{2}|u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and compute 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}^{-}(u_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Or we can just do the Gibbs sampling trick where we take 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}|u_{2}$
\end_inset

 then the other way round.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Logistic losses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula \[
s(u)=\sum\frac{\alpha u^{\beta}}{1-u^{\beta}}=\sum\frac{\alpha}{u^{-\beta}-1}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Iso--loss curves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimation in old notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 take the observations 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and initially transform to the quantiles 
\begin_inset Formula \[
u\equiv F_{*}(y)=G_{\lambda}(\chi_{1}^{2}+\lambda\cdot\eps)\ .\]

\end_inset

 Next, for given 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 transform 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
G_{\theta}^{-}(u)=(G_{\theta}^{-}\circ G_{\lambda})(\chi_{1}^{2}+\lambda\cdot\eps)\approx(G_{\theta}^{-}\circ G_{\lambda})(\chi_{1}^{2})+(G_{\theta}^{-}\circ G_{\lambda})'(\chi_{1}^{2})\lambda\cdot\eps\ .\]

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\lambda$
\end_inset

 then this reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{1}^{2}+\lambda\cdot\eps$
\end_inset

 which has the known distribution.
 Hopefully things are invariant to the base category.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this formulation 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is unknown.
 To estimate it proceed as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{ge}

\end_inset

) holds 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\eps}_{t}(\lambda)\sim N(0,I)$
\end_inset

.
 So the aim is to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

