Generalizations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally suppose 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y=(F_{*}^{-}\circ G_{\lambda})(X\chi_{1}^{2}+H\eps)\ ,\qquad\eps\sim N(0,I)\label{ge2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 To estimate we
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Bivariate copulas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are scalar random variables.
 The aim is to synthesize a bivariate copula with required properties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula \[
(G_{X+Y}\circ G_{X}^{-})(u)\equiv G_{X+Y}\{ G_{X}^{-}(u)\}\ .\]

\end_inset

 This is the quantile in the 
\begin_inset Formula $X+Y$
\end_inset

 distribution if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is at quantile 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 distribution and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{Y}(0)=0$
\end_inset

 (ie 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\ge0$
\end_inset

) it is the minimum quantile of 
\begin_inset Formula $X+Y$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is at quantile 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are independent chi--squareds each with 1 degree of freedom.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X+Y$
\end_inset

 is chi--squared with 2 degrees of freedom.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{X+Y}\circ G_{X}^{-})(u)$
\end_inset

 is the chi-squared 2 degrees of freedom distribution evaluated at quantile
 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 of the chi-squared 1 degree of freedom distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim\chi_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\sim N(0,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(G_{X+Y}\circ G_{X}^{-})(u)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{1}^{2}+N(0,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

 distribution evaluated at quantile 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{X+Y}\{ G_{X}^{-}(u)+G_{Y}^{-}(v)\}$
\end_inset

.
 This the quantile of 
\begin_inset Formula $X+Y$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is at quantile 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is at quantile 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{X+Y}\{ G_{X}^{-}(u)+Y\}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a random variable -- the quantile in the 
\begin_inset Formula $X+Y$
\end_inset

 distribution when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is at quantile 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 distribution.
 Further 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\left[G_{X+Y}\{ G_{X}^{-}(u)+Y\}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Var\left[G_{X+Y}\{ G_{X}^{-}(u)+Y\}\right]$
\end_inset

 are the expected value and variance of the quantile in the 
\begin_inset Formula $X+Y$
\end_inset

 distribution if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is at quantile 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 distribution, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim\chi_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\sim N(0,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\E[G_{X+Y}\{ G_{X}^{-}(u)+Y\}]=u\ ,\qquad Var[G_{X+Y}\{ G_{X}^{-}(u)+Y\}]=\]

\end_inset

 To prove the first relation, note that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P\{ G_{X}^{-}(u)+Y<y\}=P(Y<y-G_{X}^{-}(u)\}=G_{Y}\{ y-G_{X}^{-}(u)\}\ .\]

\end_inset

 that is a shifted version of 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Runoff triangles and copulas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the liability distribution associated with runoff triangle 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
