\begin_layout Subsection*
Conditional Probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have a risk vector 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $u=F_{*}(y)$
\end_inset

.
 Then the marginal distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 are uniform.
 Next choose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 We then have an effect on the conditional distributions of the remainder.
 Hence construct 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}(u|u_{1})$
\end_inset

 which again have uniform marginals, albeit of one dimension less.
 The advantage is that if the effect of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 is simple on all the uniform marginals then we can keep track of everything
 and hopefully
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Example copulas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Clayton
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This depends on a single parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 and is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C(u)\equiv\left(\Sigma u^{-\delta}-d+1\right)^{-1/\delta}\]

\end_inset

 It is the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula \[
u=\left\{ 1-\frac{\ln(v)}{\gamma}\right\} ^{-1/\delta}\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\sim\Gamma(\delta^{-1},1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\sim U^{d}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 In the last step things are done componentwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gumbel
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This also depends on a single parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 and is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C(u)\equiv\exp\left[\left\{ -\Sigma(-\ln u)^{\delta}\right\} ^{1/\delta}\right]\ ,\qquad\delta\ge1\ .\]

\end_inset

 It is the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula \[
u=\exp\left\{ -\left(-\frac{\ln v}{s}\right)^{1/\delta}\right\} \ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s\sim Stable$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\sim U^{d}(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that for a bivariate copula 
\begin_inset Formula $f(v|u)=f(u,v)/f(u)=f(u,v)=f(u|v)$
\end_inset

.
 Choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $u\sim f(u)$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $v\sim f(v|u)$
\end_inset

 produces a draw 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)\sim f(u,v)$
\end_inset

.
 But how do we constrain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So why does
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One distribution is the beta distribution 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(v|u)=cv^{\alpha-1}(1-v)^{\beta-1}\ ,\qquad\E(v|u)=\frac{\alpha}{\alpha+\beta}\ ,\qquad\cov(v|u)=\frac{\alpha\beta}{(\alpha+\beta)^{2}(\alpha+\beta+1)}\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>0$
\end_inset

.
 Now we want to make 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 A way of doing this is to put 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-1=-a\ln(u)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta-1=-b\ln(1-u)$
\end_inset

 to yield 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\ln\{ f(v|u)\}=c-a\ln(u)\ln(v)-b\ln(1-u)\ln(1-v)=\ln\{ f(u|v)\}\ .\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $0<u<1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now 
\begin_inset Formula $0<x<1$
\end_inset

 and hence consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=x/(1-x)$
\end_inset

 implying 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-1=(2x-1)/(1-x)$
\end_inset

.
 Note when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/2$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-1=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(y|x)=cy^{(2x-1)/(1-x)}\ .\]

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y|x)=1$
\end_inset

.
 As
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Point is to relate 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and/or 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the conditioning variable.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases we want the mean to increase and vice versa.
 So maybe make 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=x/(1-x)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1$
\end_inset

 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-1=1/(x-1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(y|x)=cy^{1/(x-1)}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However further useful information is provided by 
\begin_inset Formula $P(U_{3}>u|U_{2}>u)$
\end_inset

.
 Natural questions that arise are: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is the fact that we are conditioning both on 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 important? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What are the critical 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 points to be considered? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How do we measure consistency of choice across the different combinations?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we do have tables as above how do we combine them? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining tables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sampling scheme: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Select random 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 from the uniform 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Find max table 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}>u$
\end_inset

 in the table 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With the table probability select 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus if it makes it 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{u}$
\end_inset

 times more likely then since 
\begin_inset Formula $P(U_{2}>u)=1-u$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P(U_{2}>u|U_{1}>u)=x_{u}(1-u)\ ,\qquad P(U_{2}\le u|U_{1}>u)=1-x_{u}(1-u)\ .\]

\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{P(U_{2}>u|U_{1}>u)}{P(U_{2}\le u|U_{1}>u)}=\frac{x_{u}(1-u)}{1-x_{u}(1-u)}\ .\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Mortality smoothing with copulas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a matrix of mortality measurements with rows indicating age 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and columns time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Define column vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 as column 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and row 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 There are two ways of smoothing the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Age copula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The copula 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 models correlation across age and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}=F_{*}^{-}u_{t}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}\sim C$
\end_inset

.
 Age specific behavior across time defines the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 and are estimated from the ergodic average 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}_{*}(s)=\Ex[y_{t}<s]$
\end_inset

.
 Special cases are: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Time profiles the same for each age: 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}=1\odot h$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a scalar function and estimated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}(s)\equiv\Ex\{\hat{F}_{*}(s)\}=\Ex\{\Ex[y_{t}<s]\}$
\end_inset

 where the outer expectation is the ensemble, across age, average.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{pd}

\end_inset

 Perfect dependence across age.
 This implies all the component time series in 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 are driven by a single source of noise: 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}=1v_{t}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}\sim U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{ind}

\end_inset

 Independence across age implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}\sim\Pi$
\end_inset

.
 This model invokes the unlikely assumption that each age moves independently
 over time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The meta--Gaussian model correlation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 models the contemporaneous correlation between ages with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}=\Ex(z_{t}z_{t}')$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

 are the normits 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}\equiv(\Phi_{*}^{-}\circ F_{*})y_{t}\sim\Phi^{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Generally the correlation between close ages is higher.
 An extreme case is where the correlation between ages 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{|i-j|}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\rho\le1$
\end_inset

.
 The case 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=1$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{pd}

\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{ind}

\end_inset

 above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Serial copula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The copula 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 models serial correlation and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=F_{*}^{-}u_{i}$
\end_inset

 where draws 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}\sim C$
\end_inset

 correspond to different ages.
 Time specific mortality curves are the components in 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 and are estimated from the ensemble (age profile) average 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}_{*}(j)\equiv\Ex[y_{i}<j]$
\end_inset

.
 Special cases are: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Age profiles are the same across time.
 This implies each marginal in 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the same: 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}=1\odot h$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is univariate and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1\odot h)y_{i}$
\end_inset

 applies 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 componentwise.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=(1\odot h)^{-}u_{i}=(1\odot h^{-})u_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Function 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is estimated from the ergodic average of the empirical ensemble (age profile)
 distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}(j)\equiv\Ex\{\hat{F}_{*}(j)\}=\Ex\{\Ex[y_{i}<j]\}$
\end_inset

 where the outer 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ex$
\end_inset

 works across the components of the vector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Perfect serial dependence implies 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}=1v_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\sim U$
\end_inset

.
 Combined with a single age profile yields 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=(1\odot h^{-})1v_{i}=1h^{-}v_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 in the meta--Gaussian model is a serial covariance matrix, estimated from
 the normits 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}\equiv(\Phi_{*}^{-}\circ F_{*})y_{i}\sim\Phi^{R}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}=\Ex(z_{i}z_{i}')$
\end_inset

.
 With a fixed mortality curve 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}=\{\Phi_{*}^{-}\circ(1\odot h)\} y_{i}$
\end_inset

 implying each component of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is transformed with a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
With the meta--Gaussian model the stationary AR(1) case is where entry 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,s)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{|t-s|}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\rho\le1$
\end_inset

.
 Estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is derived from 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 by averaging the first off diagonal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which copula modelling is likely to be more appropriate? Copulas are preferred
 for variables which have distinct marginal behavious.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Modelling age at death
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{t}(i)$
\end_inset

 be the age--at--death distributions at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and from this define 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of marginals corresponding to different points of time.
 Corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=F_{*}^{-}u_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}\sim C$
\end_inset

 write, for each age 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 as the vector with components 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{t}(i)$
\end_inset

.
 A copula 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 serves to model dependence across age.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above approach serves to define 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 from the physically constructed age at death distribution, not actual deaths.
 Of course the physical age--at--death distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Connection to usual studies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distribution of age--at-death in a given year is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F(y)=P(Y<y)=\sum_{x}P(Y<y|X=x)P(X=x)=\int_{x}F(y|x)f(x)\]

\end_inset

 Differentiating with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 implies the density is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(y)=\int_{x}f(y|x)f(x)\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F(y|x)F_{X}(x)]-\int_{x}f(y|x)F_{X}(x)\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mortality smoothing across time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Time dependence is introduced by assuming 
\begin_inset Formula \[
N_{*}y_{t}=Z\alpha_{t}+G\eps_{t}\ ,\qquad\alpha_{t+1}=T\alpha_{t}+H\eps_{t}\ .\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{*}\equiv\Phi_{*}^{-}\circ F_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the steps in this process are that we first construct the normits
 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{*}y_{t}$
\end_inset

 from each of the ages over time.
 We then fit a standard state space model to these normits.
 But there must be a cycle here since the normits are estimated over time.
 Given a forecast 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}_{t}$
\end_inset

 of the normits the forecast of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}_{t}=N_{*}^{-}\hat{z}_{t}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{*}^{-}\equiv(\Phi_{*}^{-}\circ F_{*})^{-}=F_{*}^{-}\circ\Phi_{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative is to define 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{+}=\Phi_{*}^{-}\circ F_{+}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{+}$
\end_inset

 computes the quantiles of all the available data considered as one group.
 Thus the measurement equation becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{+}y_{t}=Z\alpha_{t}+G\eps_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A very simple model is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
N_{*}y_{t}=1\alpha_{t}+G\eps_{t}\ ,\qquad\alpha_{t+1}=\rho\alpha_{t}+\eta_{t}\ .\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
BvN
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Theorem 1: The Birkhoff - von Neumann Theorem [Marcus (1960), pg.
 215] A doubly stochastic matrix A can be expressed as , where are nonnegative
 real numbers summing to 1 and are permutation matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore any copula can be discretized and represented in matrix form based
 on the partition into regions of equal size.
 Then, this matrix can be decomposed into linear combination of permutation
 matrices which can enhance the understanding of dependence structure and
 help to form a basis for multivariate data analysis.
 In the following sections we will set up BvN decomposition and copula connectio
n, study the dependence bones and skeletons, discuss implications of the
 decomposition and generating copulas, and propose an approach to decompose
 copulas.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Power copulas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a copula.
 For positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 consider 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a distribution on the unit hypercube.
 The marginals are not uniform.
 However we can construct the copula 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C^{(p)}\equiv C^{p}\circ C_{*}^{p-}\]

\end_inset

 What is the dependence structure here? The procedure is thus: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Choose a given copula 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 For example 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\Phi^{R}\circ\Phi_{*}^{-}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Power it.
 For example 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}=(\Phi^{R}\circ\Phi_{*}^{-})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Note powering it means take the appropriate pointwise power not taking
 the function twice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Turn the powered version into a copula.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use the copula to model dependence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Tail correlation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want an effective method to construct the correlation in the tail of
 a distribution.
 For example when dealing with the Gaussian distribution there is a single
 correlation that describes the strength of the relationship no matter where
 you are in the distribution.
 How can we model the situation where there is more correlation in the tails?
 Here is a try.
 Think of the bivariate situation.
 Divide the unit square into smaller squares.
 In each square we correlate the normits of the quantiles.
 Thus in each little square we have a bivariate normal and we compute the
 correlation.
 To get the overall correlation we correlate the correlations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is this effective? One way to think about things is to think about 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tau(x,y)\equiv P(X>x|Y>y)=\frac{P(X>x,Y>y)}{P(S>y)}=\frac{S(x,y)}{S(y)}\]

\end_inset

 What is a smooth way of perturbing the normal to get more emphasis in the
 tail.
 One way of doing this is to think of the distribution on each margin and
 then multiply by another distribution 
\begin_inset Formula \[
G\circ F\]

\end_inset

 Call 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tail emphasizer." In the extreme for example we can have 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 as a step function with knot 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 Then result is a distribution which places a discrete mass at the knot
 and then as usual.
 What if we take a ramp function...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that a copula is a function of many variables and returns a probability.
 So you can't apply a copula repeatedly.
 What happens if you take a copula 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and and generate a second copula from it.
 That is you construct 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{C}\equiv C\circ C_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 But the marginals 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{*}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 are uniform.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{C}=C\circ I=C$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What about taking a Gaussian copula and applying it repeatedly? For example
 
\begin_inset Formula $G\equiv\Phi^{R}\circ\Phi_{*}^{-}$
\end_inset

 is the Gaussian copula with correlation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Using What about 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a copula.
 Hence it takes probabilities to probabilities.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{p}$
\end_inset

 is a copula for any integer 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Note 
\begin_inset Formula $G^{0}=I$
\end_inset

, the uniform copula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Survival copulas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Copulas are typically thought of as the joint distribution on the square.
 Alternatively let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 denote a survival function: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
S(y)=P(Y>y)\]

\end_inset

 We can then think of a survival copula on the square.
 Thus a survival copula is a survival function on the unit cube with uniform
 marginals.
 Note for positive random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $S(0)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S(y)\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $y\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim S$
\end_inset

, indicating 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a random vector with survival function 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

survival" transform 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P\{ S(Y)>y\}=P\{ Y<S^{-}(y)\}=1-S\{ S^{-}(y)\}=1-y\]

\end_inset

 Thus let 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 be a survival copula on the unit hypercube with uniform marginals and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{*}$
\end_inset

 a vector of survival marginals and define 
\begin_inset Formula \[
S_{D}\equiv D\circ S_{*}\ ,\qquad D_{S}\equiv S\circ S_{*}^{-}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Total liability distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi(s)\equiv P(\iota'F_{*}^{-}u\le s)\ ,\qquad s_{\alpha}=\phi^{-}(\alpha)\ ,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u\sim C$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\alpha\le1$
\end_inset

 is given.
 What is a good way of estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $F(s)$
\end_inset

? Further what is a good way of determining 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

? For example we may wish to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.75$
\end_inset

, the 75th percentile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One approach is to repeatedly sample 
\begin_inset Formula $u\sim C$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota'F_{*}^{-}u$
\end_inset

.
 These realizations are transformed to quantiles and in turn the quantiles
 are used to define 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we are interested in say the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 quantile then hopefully we need only consider 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in the triangular pyramid of points lying above
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also important is the copula to be used.
 What is a good copula?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can we simplify.
 For this purpose look at the 2D case and consider the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)$
\end_inset

 and suppose the quantile associated with this point insofar as the sum
 is concerned is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we move 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x-\delta$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

.
 At the same time we move 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $y+\delta$
\end_inset

 and hence the sum stays the same.
 The change in quantile in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 distribution is from 
\begin_inset Formula $u=F_{X}(x)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{X}(x-\delta)\approx F_{X}(x)-\delta f_{X}(x)=u-\delta f_{X}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 That is the change in the quantile is approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $-\delta f_{X}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly the change in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 quantile is approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta f_{Y}(y)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the relative change in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 quantile to that in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 quantile is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
-\frac{f_{Y}(y)}{f_{X}(x)}\ .\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

 and consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{s}=\{(x,y):x+y\le s\}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $(s,0)\in\Omega_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Want 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}(\Omega_{s})$
\end_inset

, the quantile set corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Note 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F_{*}(\Omega_{s})=\{ u:\iota'F_{*}^{-}u\le s\}\ .\]

\end_inset

 What does this set look like? Here we look at the 2D situation.
 First consider (in 2D) 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{s},v_{s})=F_{*}^{-}(s,s)$
\end_inset

.
 These are the intercepts points, ie the quantiles in the marginal distributions
 that yield 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(u_{s},0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,v_{s})$
\end_inset

 are in 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}(\Omega_{s})$
\end_inset

.
 Moving from 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,s)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\delta,s-\delta)$
\end_inset

 keeps us in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding movements in 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)$
\end_inset

 space is from 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,v_{s})$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\delta f_{X}(0),v_{s}-\delta f_{Y}(s))$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the slope is 
\begin_inset Formula $-f_{Y}(s)/f_{X}(0)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above argument can be generalized to any point when moving from 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)$
\end_inset

, presumed to be such that the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y=s$
\end_inset

.
 The change in 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 relative to a change in 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $-f_{Y}(x-s)/f_{X}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the boundary is defined by the differential equation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\partial v=\frac{-f_{Y}\{ F_{X}^{-}(u)-s\}}{f_{X}\{ F_{X}^{-}(u)\}}\partial u\ ,\]

\end_inset

 with starting condition 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,F_{Y}^{-}(s))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once we have the boundary then we sample repeatedly from the copula and
 check if the sampled point lies on the right side of the boundary.
 If so we count 1 and otherwise 0 and averaging we determine the quantile
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively we determine say the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 quantile in 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{Y}$
\end_inset

 called 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 say.
 We then use the above differential equation to define the boundary using
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 in place of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 We repeatedly sample from the copula and check if we are on the right side
 of the boundary and count 1 or 0.
 Averaging the 1's leads to the quantile of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 Generally expect that the quantile of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 will be much bigger than 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Interesting to see how much bigger it is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is an interesting graph.
 Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\alpha}\equiv F_{*}^{-}1\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Then compute the sum quantile from each component of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 Presumably the sum quantiles in each case are much less than 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, we simply sample from the copula and just construct 
\begin_inset Formula \[
s=\iota'F_{*}^{-}u\ ,\qquad u\sim C\ .\]

\end_inset

 and compute the quantiles associated with the generated sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{X}(s)=\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(s,0)$
\end_inset

