\begin_inset Formula $x+y\ge s$
\end_inset

.
 Decreasing 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by a small amount and increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 by the corresponding amount so as to keep the sum fixed implies the ratio
 of the percentiles changes by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
-\frac{f_{Y}(0)}{f_{X}(s)}\ .\]

\end_inset

 It is not unreasonable to suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{Y}(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the change in the percentile...
 Hence provided 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{Y}(0)<f_{X}(s)$
\end_inset

 the change in the percentile Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{X}(x_{\alpha})=\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

