\begin_layout Subsection*
Tail copulas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In liability forecasting only the upper tails of distributions are of interest.
 This motivates the use of tail copulas.
 A tail copula is a copula that joins marginal distributions in the tails.
 In particular define 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F_{\alpha}(y)=\left\{ \begin{array}{lr}
(1-\alpha)^{-1}(F_{*}-\alpha)(y)\ , & F_{*}(y)\ge\alpha\ ,\\
0\ , & F_{*}(y)<\alpha\ .\end{array}\right.\]

\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of tail marginal distributions.
 We now copulate the tail marginals as 
\begin_inset Formula $C\circ F_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 which is a distribution of
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a bivariate copula 
\begin_inset Formula $C(u,v)$
\end_inset

.
 This yields tail probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C^{\alpha}(u,v)=C(u,v|u>\alpha,v>\alpha)=\frac{C(u,v)}{1-C(0.5,0.5)+...}\]

\end_inset

 say.
 This is a joint distribution on the upper right hand square.
 We can turn this joint distribution into a copula viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C^{\alpha}\circ C_{*}^{\alpha}\qquad F_{C^{\alpha}}\equiv C^{\alpha}\circ F_{*}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Sampling from distributions generated with a copula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simulate from 
\begin_inset Formula $C\circ F_{*}$
\end_inset

, proceed as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $C=C_{1}C_{2|1}C_{3|1,2}\cdots$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\sim C_{1}\equiv U$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\sim C_{2|1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{3}\sim C_{3|1,2}$
\end_inset

 and so on leading to 
\begin_inset Formula $u\equiv(u_{1},u_{2},u_{3},\ldots,)'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Put 
\begin_inset Formula $y=F_{*}^{-}u$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim C\circ F_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The potential difficulty is finding/specifying the conditional distributions.
 What are reasonable specifications.
 How do we determine what a reasonable specification is.
 Maybe, similar to time series, we should forget about specifying a global
 copula but concentrate on just specifying a sequence of conditional copulas
 starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}=U$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C(u_{2}|u_{1})\equiv\frac{C(u_{1},u_{2})}{U(u_{1})}=\frac{C(u_{1}|u_{2})u_{2}}{u_{1}}\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad\frac{C(u_{2}|u_{1})}{C(u_{1}|u_{2})}=\frac{u_{2}}{u_{1}}\ .\]

\end_inset

 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $C(u_{2}|u_{1})\ge C(u_{1},u_{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}\sim C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}=(v_{t}',w_{t}')'$
\end_inset


\end_layout

