\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $[F(Y)>u]$
\end_inset

 is 1 if 
\begin_inset Formula $F(Y)>u$
\end_inset

 and 0 otherwise.
 Thus measures indicating the departure from independence are 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)/(1-u)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\psi(u)$
\end_inset

 while measures indicating the departure from perfect dependence are 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\psi(u)/(1+u)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi(u)=\frac{P\{ F(Y)>u,F(X)>u\}}{P\{ F(X)>u\}}=\frac{P\{ F(Y)>u,F(X)>u\}}{1-u}\ .\]

\end_inset

 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 This is not a property enjoyed by the other two measures of tail dependence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note 
\begin_inset Formula $2\psi(u)-\phi(u)=u$
\end_inset

 for both perfectly dependent and independent situations.
 Alternatively 
\begin_inset Formula $2\psi(u)+\phi(u)=2-u$
\end_inset

 if independent and 
\begin_inset Formula $2+u$
\end_inset

 if perfectly dependent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A further variant is the moment generating type function 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\E\{\e^{sF(Y)}|F(X)>u\}\ ,\qquad\\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, the conditional probability is estimated as the empirical proportion of
 the quantiles of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 that exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 given the empirical quantile of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 exceeds 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 approaches 1, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)$
\end_inset

 may approach some number bigger than 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's define the normits as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By Bayes' theorem 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi(u)=\frac{P\{ F(X)>u|F(Y)>u\}}{P\{ F(X)>u\}}P\{ F(Y)>u\}\ .\]

\end_inset

 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi_{Y|X}(u)=\phi_{X|Y}(u)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)\equiv1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are perfectly dependent while 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)=1-u$
\end_inset

 under independence.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)$
\end_inset

 measures the percentage reduction in dependence while 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)/(1-u)$
\end_inset

 measures how far things are away from independence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P\{ F(X)>u,F(Y)>u\}=P\{ F(X)>u\} P\{ F(Y)>u|F(X)>u\}=(1-u)\phi(u)\ .\]

\end_inset

 This implies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly we can define 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\qquad\rho(u)\equiv\mathrm{cor}\{ F(X),F(Y)|F(X)>u\}\ .\]

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are independent 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(u)=0.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(u)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Positive tail dependence is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'(u)>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
0.5=\psi(u)(1-u)+\E\{ F(Y)|F(X)<u\} u\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad E\{ F(Y)|F(X)<u\}=\frac{0.5-\psi(u)(1-u)}{u}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When there is perfect dependence between 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(u)=(1+u)/2$
\end_inset

.
 Hence a reasonable measure of tail dependence is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{2\psi(u)}{1+u}\]

\end_inset

 If there is perfect tail dependence then this should be close to 1.
 If there is no tail dependence then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(u)=1/2$
\end_inset

 and this measure is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/(1+u)$
\end_inset

 which approaches 1/2 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When there is dependence between 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\E\{ F(Y)|F(X)>u\}$
\end_inset

 will increase with 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Theoretically the expression is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
=\frac{P\{ F(X)>u,F(Y)>u\}}{P\{ F(Y)>u\}}\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
=\lim_{u\uparrow1}\frac{1-P\{ F(X)<u\}-P\{ F(Y)<u\}+P\{ F(X)<u,F(Y)<u\}}{1-P\{ F(Y)<u\}}=\lim_{u\uparrow1}\frac{1-2u+C(u,u)}{1-u}\ .\]

\end_inset

 An empirical estimate is to take the proportion of cases where all quantiles
 exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 of the proportion of cases For an empirical estimate we do the following:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each quantile 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 determine the proportion of cases where both variables have a bigger quantile
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Divide by the proportion proportion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 variables have bigger quantile 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Simulating using a Gaussian copula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the correlation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is given and 
\begin_inset Formula $z\sim\Phi^{R}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{*}(z)\sim\Phi^{R}\circ\Phi_{*}^{-}$
\end_inset

.
 To prove this consider 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P\{\Phi_{*}(z)<u\}=P\{ z<\Phi_{*}^{-}(u)\}=\Phi^{R}\{\Phi_{*}^{-}(u)\}=(\Phi^{R}\circ\Phi_{*}^{-})(u)\ ,\]

\end_inset

 as required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we take 
\begin_inset Formula $z\sim\Phi^{R}$
\end_inset

 and consider 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Each component has a chi--squared distribution and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\chi_{*}^{-}(z^{2})$
\end_inset

 has uniform marginals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Copulas for runoff triangles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Measurement noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In many cases it is appropriate to add 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measurement" noise.
 For example 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{t}=F_{*}^{-}u_{t}+F_{*}^{-}\eps_{t}\ ,\qquad u_{t}\sim C\ ,\qquad\eps_{t}\sim\Pi\ .\]

\end_inset

 In the case of the Gaussian copula a signal plus noise model is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{t}=(F_{*}^{-}\circ\Phi_{*})(\sqrt{R-\sigma^{2}I}\zeta_{t}+\sigma\xi_{t})\ ,\qquad(\zeta_{t}',\xi_{t}')'\sim\Phi^{I}\ .\]

\end_inset

 Thus the covariance matrix of the overall disturbance is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 In this formulation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 cannot exceed the smallest eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 A further refinement is where the copula from which 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

 is drawn is a conditional copula.
\end_layout

